Parliament Does Not Support Tymoshenko Freedom amendment
Today, the Ukraine parliament dismissed, within the Code of Criminal Procedure amendment, the motion to revoke an article based on which the opposition leader, Yulia Tymoshenko, was sentenced.
The amendment that would lead to the release of the former Prime Minister was revoked during second reading of the proposal for reducing economic offences sentences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for entering into a disadvantageous gas deal with Russia.
The verdict is not yet final, and the court will hear Tymoshenko's appeal in December.
Tymoshenko claims the verdict is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the trial has also evoked suspicion of bias.
The proposal to remove Article 365 from the Code of Criminal Procedure, upon which the former Prime Minister was sentenced, was supported by 147 members of the parliament.
It would require 226 votes.
