Brand Story:
The IMB Innovator Begins Second Century of Its Existence
Should someone search for a word that best describes the IMB strategy, the most close one would be "long-term."
The wide public, IMB is a symbol of technological revolution; the company is seen as a highly temporary one, but it was founded over 100 years ago.
The company’s stability is linked to its first boss, a visionary, Thomas J. Watson Sr.
The philosophy of his life was that many world problems can be solved if people are willing to think.
The motto: 'Think!' becomes an iprint around which the future giant would unfold (as well as the name of its internal magazine that IMB started to publish in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the company culture Watson was building carefully.
IMB long term thinking means continuing movement towards the future.
IMB survived and flourished for a hundred years, because it remained true to its original values, and it was not afraid to change everything around it.
During our first century, this allowed us to transform technology, business, and the company.
In the second century we hope to achieve even more, says current company Director Samuel J. Palmisano.
Sophisticated System
In 1930s, Watson approached employee care similarly to Baťa in Czech Republic - people from IMB were among the first American employees to have paid holiday, insurance from their employer, elegant uniform, and a complex system of rewards for the best inventors and businessmen.
As sophisticated is IBM's long-term relationship with customers.
From the very start, the company was brilliant in finding talented people. It was one of the first world companies to eliminate all discrimination, which provided it with great selection.
Following the anti-discrimination strategy is the current plan for a woman, Virginia Rometty, to take over after Palmisano next year.
She has been working in IMB for 30 years, and is currently Director of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years, IMB has been organising jams, on-line brainstorm sessions, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
It is no surprise that the ideas are plentiful - the company employs nearly half a million people.
Good Reputation Institution
The Company's strong business position is ensured by its strong internal and external image.
The beginning of IBM was a institution, but the concept of the company was that of a institution rather than a technology company,' a Harvard Business School Professor and author of the book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter, told the Economist.
IBM is not a technology firm, but a company that helps solve business problems with technology.
As the company says, there is a difference between entering a market and creating it.
During the past 100 years, IMB, or the "Big Blue" as it is called in the US, has grown into one of the world's most important companies.
It seems to be the most universal technology company - developing hardware and software; infrastructure; hosting; and consultation services within a range from servers to nanotechnologies.
It has the most patents of all American technology companies; five of its employees were awarded the Nobel Prize.
It is known to include cash point, pay card, financial swap, and floppy disc.
With about 220 billion dollars, based on market capitalisation, IBM has become the second largest technology company (Apple being number one) this year, overrunning Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
View ahead
However, not all its products satisfied both customers and period.
If your business is defined by movement forward, you cannot be emotionally attached to past.
It is why IBM easily builds its foundations on many platforms - if they do not work, it leaves them.
This is how it differs from, for example, Microsoft’s competitors, Microsoft, which basically stands and falls on Windows, its operating system.
Perspective Technology
IBM's revenues mainly consist of services, about one fifth of which is from software and hardware.
In 1990, with over half share, it was the strongest hardware representative.
Since 2000, IBM has sold low profitable assets worth 15 billion dollars. While the same time, it has invested 58 billion dollars into perspective technologies.
It has continued the investments even after 2008, when the modern economic crisis first hit the world.
IBM follows the legacy of its first director, Thomas J. Watson, who increased the amount of investment during the Great Depression.
So far, IMB seems to be getting through the current crisis without any harm.
Since the start of 2008, the price of IBM's shares has grown by remarkable 120 per cent; and the company's net income has been continuously growing.
IBM's company motto is to change everything, except its values.
The flexible giant may therefore expect that even if another crisis occurs, this flexible giant will manage.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Travel
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York, a hundred years ago. Its original name "Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation" was quite complicated.
It took the name of IBM in 1924, originally a brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The foundations for later IBM were laid by a merger of four companies, the history of which goes back to the 1880s.
Their technology was such as the legendary time clock, which is a clock recording the time when employees arrive and leave work.
The architect of the new company was a businessman, Charles Ranlett Flint, who, until 1930, also presided over the Board of Trustees.
