Development of Trip Prices since 1989
In 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea, and Autoturist.
As travel to the West was restricted, travel agencies mostly sold tours to the socialist block countries.
The Czech tourists took the sea to Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea near the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both to the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. However, the Yugoslavian regime changed West, which caused significant limitations to Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialistic period was that citizens of the socialist block (i.e. Czechoslovaks too) were not allowed individual travel within the socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel as individual to, for example, the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter from the country was required; otherwise, individual travel was unable.
The time, travel agencies offered some West trips, but one either had to stand in line overnight, with a sleeping bag or have some good friends in the agency.
Still, that was not all.
The foreign currency assurance was essential for travel to the West, but it was not granted to unreliable people, who were not allowed to travel at all.
Czech Republic currency was not freely converted; without the currency assurance, it was unable to obtain financial means (Western currency) for travelling West.
Most Czechs spent their holiday home, resulting in a large number of cottages and summer houses, a habit that remains today.
Since 1989 Czech tourism has experienced a real revolution.
While in 1989, a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the climax of our travels, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries all over the world.
The great paradox we do not realize is that until 1989, we could not freely visit the currently most popular Croatia, as it was part of former Yugoslavia.
The first few years after the 1990s, visas for neighbouring West European countries were cancelled. This started a large wave of short-term visits to Vienna and Germany.
Everyone wanted to travel to the West for a moment.
In Paris Czech tours slept in parks in tents, because they had no money to pay for a hotel or pension.
The Czech tourism typical feature was bringing their own food (cans, salami, etc.) to save money.
The second important event was the introductory of freely converted Czech Crown. After years, tourists finally could freely buy Western currencies.
Our living standards and average income were growing, which, around 1997, resulted in another important moment.
Since 1997, increasing demand allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights by charter airlines.
After 1990s Czechs no longer needed visas for visiting nearly all developed world countries, except for USA. This made travel even easier.
Next significant event in the history of after revolution travelling occurred in 2000. High demand resulted in the first direct charter flight from Czech Republic to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights take Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter, Czech tourists will travel to twelve exotic destinations.
Currently about 100 thousand Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
The next important event in this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, occurred in 2008.
On November 17, USA removed visas for Czech tourists. Our country has thus become permanently a member of the world's most developed countries.
First time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (51.3%) and for the first time in history they spent over 15 thousand Crowns per person per holiday abroad, including their costs at the destination.
