Should Deutsche Bank stop trading agriculture commodities?
According to SPIEGEL ONLINE, Josef Ackermann has given a working group the task of investigating the consequences of speculation for poor people around the world.
The CEO plans to make changes in January.
Hamburg - -
The situation is clear. According to one study, 84 percent of Germans do not accept that banks speculate on agriculture commodities such as wheat and maize.
The majority of the questioned demand that Deutsche Bank and other banks stop trading in agriculture, as trading deepens the problems faced by the poorest people in the world.
The findings were made in a survey conducted by the Forsa Institute for Social Research and Statistical Analysis on behalf of Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid October.
The author of the report, Harald Schumann, shows that betting on global commodities exchanges drives prices - and banks are thus complicit in global hunger.
The campaign by consumer advocates is aimed at the head of Deutsche Bank, Josef Ackermann, but large banking houses such as Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley also trade in the same way.
Initially, commodity betting was designed to protect traders against price fluctuations.
However, most experts now agree that the gamblers have left behind the supply and demand rules and are taking a huge profit at the cost of the poorest.
In contrast to US competitors, Ackermann has responded to the criticism, promise to investigate the claims and has given no trade to risk the good reputation of Deutsche Bank.
According to SPIEGEL ONLINE, an international working group is currently investigating the accusations contained in the Foodwatch report.
The investigation should be completed by the end of the year, when the findings will be presented to Deutsche Bank's Management Board with recommendations for action.
The head of the bank plans to announce changes following the investigation at the end of January.
Commodity trading may be reduced or stopped completely.
