21st House in Vienna
The relocated pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
The Austrian Pavilion for the 1958 World's Fair in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and was abandoned.
Now it is reopened as an exhibition centre.
Austria's pavilion, designed by Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World's Fair, is a famous textbook example of modern post-war architecture with its clear shapes, glass halls, bold strokes and new construction materials.
Schwanzer's pavilion won the Grand Prix d'Architecture in 1958 for its light floating steel-glass structure.
The building is considered a milestone in contemporary architecture.
It made the architect so famous that he also built Austria's pavilion at the next world fair.
Then he finally took international fame with his legendary four-cylinder BMW Tower and its bowl-shaped sister building.
The pavilion, which was designed as a temporary exhibition building, was relocated to the Schweizer Garten near Vienna's Südbahnhof, converted and opened as the 20th Century Museum in 1962 - and is widely referred to as the 20er Haus.
However, the building was not suitable for museum for technical and spatial reasons - it had no walls to hang artworks and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until contemporary art in Vienna was given a new home.
The building remained empty from 2001 and went into a worse and worse state of repair.
The architect Adolf Krischanitz has now renovated the pavilion, which has been named the 21er Haus and will be used as a contemporary art museum.
The museum is a branch of the Belvedere museum, which will open the first exhibition on Tuesday evening - a delight in every respect.
Agnes Huslein-Arco who became the new Director of Austrian Galerie Belvedere in 2007 was instrumental in the new start.
Arco, an art history graduate with a remarkable career in ice skating, went on to Sotheby's, Guggenheim Museum and to become the founding director of the Museum of Moderne in Salzburg, convinced politicians and conservators to continue with the renovation, attracting public funding and private sponsorship and decided on the use of the building.
The new museum was to house the permanent collection of the Fritz Wotruba Foundation, a café and bookshop, alongside contemporary art.
Strict supervision & limited budget
Krischanitz was then the ideal choice to carry out the project.
The most important thing for him was to renovate and expand Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna, and won the competition.
The original design was known and knew the issues the building was facing.
The latest changes have been much more serious. The building was "a energy guzzler," says Krischanitz.
The window profile of the glass facade was replaced, fibreglass-reinforced safety glass was placed in and the glass roof was replaced with high-grade safety glass.
Thermal bridge steel girders were strengthened or replaced and asbestos was removed from ceilings.
The two lower floors created space for new use of the building, a sunken light well between the building and the street provides lighting, and a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building but still the delicate Schwanzer pavilion.
The original external doors have been retained and the building has been painted in the old red-brown colour of rust-proofing.
The cinema hall is exactly as it used to be.
All this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a limited budget.
They often wanted to find material that was good, cheap and meets the approval of the monument authority.
The building has remained flexible and light despite the restrictions, problems and changes.
Krischanitz recently stated that the pavilion was tough - a typical "drop in the city story".
Architects like this are always in the wrong place, but nonetheless want to "stimulate real awareness."
The 21er Haus is very much in the right place, as there has been a stroke of luck in town planning.
The 21er Haus may also be a second stroke of luck, as the collector Francesca von Habsburg has acquired the Temporäre Kunsthalle Berlin and is reported to be negotiating with the city for a neighbouring location in the Schweizer Garten.
