The intensive and hugely emotional new book, The Beauty and Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a long, dramatic personae that can make your heart sink.
Here is advice for proceeding: Gently excise this page and make it your bookmark.
The persons you will know are very well known in Mr Englund's novelistic telling, and this dramatis personae will function as your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when you are confused and stunned in the fog of war.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
The new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awardes the Nobel Prize in Literature.
What he has written here is an unusual book, one he describes not inaccurately as "anti-history work."
The list is limited to big names, major treaties or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, silly journalists or debate on tactics and material.
It is not so much a book about what happened as a book about what it was like. It is about "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
The Beauty and Sorrow" threads together the experiences of 20 unremarkable men and women, from schoolgirls and botanists to mountain climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and clerks.
Some of these people will become heroes.
A few will become prisoners of war, or lose limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flicker here like candles lighting in a church; new ones are added to the mix while some wink out.
Mr Englund's book is a deviation from standard history books.
It is a corrective to the notion that World War I was only about the dreadful trench warfare on the Western Front.
The Beauty and Sorrow successfully spreads across other theatres of war: the Alps, Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Warriors in the book have beehives fall on them; one has Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are a serious problem.
This is a moving book, almost from the start.
The War floods these people's lives like a natural catastrophe, a Hurricane Katrina that reeks of cordite.
If you are a woman at home with children, do you stay or flee?
Who is coming, anyway?
Almost no one understands what is happening, even why this war is to be fought.
Facts have been covered with guesses, supppositions, fears, illusions, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors.
The Beauty and Sorrow follows individuals like Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian Army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German high-seas carrier seaman.
Their stories are mostly taken from memoirs, letters and other already published material.
The accounts of their lives can be threatening or stirring, but most fully alive are in Mr. Englund's accumulation of small moments, sparse details.
Many of these are about deprivation and doing.
In telling a German schoolgirl's story he says: "Replace, everywhere replace."
"Replace coffee, fake aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
The speech is about the ersatz food in Germany.
The describes "rice cooked in mutton fat (finished with a fake bone made of wood); tobacco made of dried roots and dried potato peel; shoes soles with wood."
There are, he notes, "837 registered meat substitutes permissible in the production of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes."
Some stories about honor and bravery.
One American recognises his own desire to savagery and declares about war: "You feel that after all, this is what men were intended for, rather than to sit in easy chairs with a cigarette and whiskey, the evening paper or the best seller, and to pretend that there is no barbarian behind your stained and studded shirt front.
Conversely a British soldier believes that he will most likely die, and no one will notice or care.
Once one is resigned to the thought of sacrificing oneself, one would like to think that it might happen in front of an audience.
Instead, it is horribly like "a condemned man being secretly swollen."
Other observations are about an old Europe going away, and about new types of terror.
The conflict has increasingly become an economic competition, Mr Englund says, "a war between factories."
The arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the young century: the articulate and ideologically convinced mass murderer in well-cut clothes who performs his butchery while sitting behind a desk."
People act in unexpected ways; there is as much base behavior as heroism.
Commander Englund discussed the soldiers who actively try to catch venereal disease from prostitutes as a way to evade service at the front.
The most tragic expression of this is in the trade of gonococcal pus, which soldiers buy and smear into their genitals in order to end up in hospital.
"Those who are really desperate rub it into their eyes, which often results in lifelong blindness."
In this translation from the Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund's prose is supple but unshown, very well suited to his human task.
In several small scenes he catches how the war has "uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred."
People begin to ask why their leaders are making them fight.
The best books about World War I have often been either negative, like Paul Fussell's Great War and Modern Memory, or novels, like Erich Maria Remarque's All Quiet on the Western Front, rather than comprehensive historical accounts.
Mr Englund's volume joins an unconventional pantheon.
The most devastating end I can remember in a nonfiction book.
I will not give it away.
It is as if he has reached from his book, snatched that dramatis personae page from your finger, and lighted it with a match.
