Shutters have Eyes: How Researchers Are Studying You on Facebook
Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy spreading his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to a July killing spree in Norway that left 77 people dead, faces his first public hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: he spent much of his time leading up to his attack at his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After this summer tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
How do they get them?
Easy - just log on to Facebook.
Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by British think tank DEMOS.
However, the database is so huge, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to pinpoint their target population with scientific accuracy - the way marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then targeted them with ads, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the ads asked users to complete a survey that asked questions about their education level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their future.
By reaching through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues could survey over 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
It is quite new way of doing research, Bartlett says.
Some results are not all that surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male, and very sensitive to immigration.
In a twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind the computer screen.
DEMOS’ work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a hot new tool in the hands of scientists.
The site is used by think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists to study everything from health issues to social trends as expressed in 'Likes', wall posts and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding average three pieces of content per day, the Facebook data supernova is generating a research boom, driving the number of academic papers with the site's name in the title up almost 80% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it lets you study people you cannot approach with a clipboard on the street.
Before, when you try to survey people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them.
They would never allow you access to the party.
"Facebook cuts all that out - you go directly to them."
Others believe the site could offer a way to identify and tackle social health problems.
The recent study by Dr Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison and her colleagues found that undergraduates who discussed their drinking exploits on Facebook were significantly more at risk for problem drinking than students who remained silent on the topic.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as residential advisors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who posts too many boozy status updates.
Dimitri Christakis, co-author and Director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, told the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise be diagnosed.
Facebook is constantly tapping into its own population for data.
The Data Team has worked on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in 2010 midterm, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using information only it can access - champions of digital freedom have long held that the site should make its vast trove of data available to others for research.)
The site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the trade off for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
What about when Facebook users become part of a survey they do not even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines about how they collect their data offline, online it is free for all.
Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, says of a 2006 study conducted using students' public Facebook profiles.
As far as they were concerned, it was just between them and their friends.
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research subject is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of a user's profile information and wall posts are true.
'What you say on Facebook and what you do outside Facebook are two completely different things' says Selwyn.
The reason is that, despite his years as a technology researcher, clipboard and pen are still the best research tools any person can use.
There is no alternative to going into the real world and speaking to real people.
"Social research is supposed to be about the social - and a hell of a lot of the social still occurs offline."
