7 Lessons From the Lost Steve Jobs Interview, Showing at a Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs’ death on Oct. 5, some people compared him to Henry Ford - calling him the Great Modern Inventor.
The most revealing thing to Apple fans is the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was released in advance of special movie screenings in major markets this week, about how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
The man was certainly a designer, dreamer and self-described hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and flow-chart tweaker - a man who believed that many business executives suffered from "a disease of thinking that a really great idea is 90% of the work... but there is a tremendous amount of crafting between a great idea and a great product."
Then in 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the TV series Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a rare, long conversation.
At that time it had been roughly 10 years since Jobs was forced out of Apple, and he was already working at his new computer company NeXT, looking to the growing adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he says that the master copy of the interview went missing in shipping.
The VHS was only found after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly reedited, is the basis of the 68-minute Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, coming to Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to loathe detailed interviews, Jobs seems to be a bit more eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
At four different points during the interview, there are major gaps between questions and answers - 10 to 15-second ruminations, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, aiming for precision.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism rises to the surface, where he seems to be anxious about Cringely's questions, leading him to move faster to issues or subplots of greater import.
The Lost Interview is a very interesting film, as Jobs assesses what other companies do and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It is one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs career, but there is something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the brink of greatness.
The vision for how things can be and should be.
After spelling it all out he went and did it.
The short list of seven Lost Interview sequences:
How he learned to run a business:
"Throughout my years in business I always ask why you do things? And the answers I always get are: "Oh, that's the way it is done.""
Nobody knows why they do what they do, nobody really thinks about things very deeply in business.
That is what I found.
Jobs continues to detail his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
When he was confused by how costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was then adjusted with a "variance" - he developed an automated factory that ensured they could determine business costs down to the second.
On pranking Pope:
Jobs recalls the "Blue Box" that he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long distance calls for free.
The device has been widely written about before, but Jobs' euphoria in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is infectious.
Then he describes how he and Wozniak would test the box by using a pay phone, placing a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while looping in as many satellites as possible.
They were going around the world half dozen times and you would yell through the pay phone and it would come through a minute later in the next door pay phone.
We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.
Us two, we didn't know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing - it was an incredible lesson, and I cannot imagine there would ever be Apple without it.
Jobs goes on to detail one glorious prank that he and Wozniak nearly pulled off, ringing the Vatican via the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope.
The two burst into laughter when the Pope himself appeared to answer the phone.
On falling in love with technology (and cold-calling Bill Hewlett):
Then at 12, while looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and gave him a call.
Then, a short phone conversation, Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
The only company I saw at that age was the only company I saw at that age and it formed my view of what a company was and how they treat their employees.
Jobs later became one of HP's employees to visit the company's Palo Alto research labs, where he saw the first desktop computer ever made.
It was as large as a suitcase, had a small cathode ray tube display, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a ride up to HP as a teenager and hang around that machine and write programs for it.
Improving innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
Early in his career, as he set out to sell a handful of circuit boards, he was asked to build the full computer.
Working on only 30 days of credit, he had to figure out both the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
After coming to Apple, he recalls the difficulties he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments...they were screaming at me that it would take five years to build a mouse that would cost $300. I got fed up and went outside and found a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse we could build for $15 that was incredibly reliable.
On great companies losing steam:
Then, before he led the revival of Apple, Jobs consciously anticipated how so many industry leaders would fall in line with their vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, you make better copier or printer, so what?"
You have a monopoly of market share, so the company is not more successful.
Sales and marketing makes it more successful, so those people who end up running companies and the product people get driven out of the decision-making forum.
The product genius that led to that monopolistic position is rotted by people who have no conception of good products vs. bad products - the craftmanship required.
That is what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, could have been Microsoft of the 90s...
They took defeat from victory.
Innovation as art form:
"There is a tremendous amount of craftmanship between a great idea and a great product... as you evolve that great idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are tradeoffs you have to make - certain things you cannot do electrons do, glass do, robots do, factories do.
You have to keep 5,000 things in your brain - these concepts - fitting them all together...
The most important thing is to try to expose yourself to the best human work, and then try to bring that into your work.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have always been shameless about stealing great ideas.
The part that made the Mac great was that the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for computer science, they would be doing amazing things in other fields.
