How to spot a lie
The recent headlines indicate how serious and pervasive deceit and lying are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy trading sexual harassment claims with several women, each side accusing the other of lying.
Auditors at Penn State have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting boys.
The French president Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on an open mic threatening to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed career and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet flasher Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by issuing denials quickly contradicted by incontrovertible evidence.
Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations connected to the cover-up of an extra-marital affair.
Then again, no one who lived through it will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton unleashed during his second term in office about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
Tales of cheating on school and college tests are rife.
There have been instances where teachers have given students test answers to make them look good on their performance reviews.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending a message that lying and cheating are accepted.
How much deceit do we get?
On a given day, studies show you may be lied to anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
Many of those are white lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times within the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Detecting lies, or "lie spotting", is an essential skill for everyone to acquire, both personal and professional reasons.
Deception detection is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities conducting in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
The result of the research is that most old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look at you in the eye.
They do not always steer, slump, smirk or fidget.
Do not conclude from this that liars are difficult to spot and unmask.
A trained lie spotter can get to the truth by learning about statement structure, facial micro-expressions, question formation and time.
Since I spent several years exploring the scientific findings in the vast and ever-growing body of deception knowledge, I have become aware that deception detection is a modern skill that can be learned and helpful in navigating our complex world, especially if you have a professional role in hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are skilled in reading others well, putting them in ease, managing their emotions and intuitively sensing how others perceive them.
According to research, extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-oriented" lies than women tell more "other-oriented" lies - usually to protect someone's feelings, and that married people lie less frequently to their partners than unmarried people do (but the lies they do tell tend to be whoppers).
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilt in lying to you.
How do you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe your subject's normal behavior.
This is called baselining.
It provides a reference point for later assessments.
Notice your subject's posture, laugh, vocal quality.
You should know if someone normally taps their foot all the time so you can avoid unjust accusations when you see foot-tapping in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clusters of deceptive verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these clusters red flags, not proof of deception.
Deceptive people may freeze their upper body when trying to remember their story, they may lean towards an exit, shift their posture in significant ways or exhibit post-interview relief - an exaggerated exhale of relief and shift in posture after all the hard questions have been answered.
Interrogators often falsely signal that an interview is over to look for post-interview relief.
Also, consider your subject's language.
Scott Peterson famously slipped and used the past tense while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
Deceptive individuals may also use distance language: " I have no sexual relations with that woman ... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a hard question in its entirety.
Most common verbal indicators are subtle.
They may use lots of "qualifying language" when answering a hard question: "Well ... I will tell you the truth as far as I know ... to the best of my knowledge."
This renders the answer perceptual rather than fact and is often a red flag.
There is no magic bullet for detecting lies, but developing skills to ferret out deception is possible.
This skills will enhance any person's chances of avoiding victimization by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
