The climate adversity slowed the economy.
During the first year of Mario Lopez Valdez management, in Sinaloa increase the unemployment and informality, foreign investment declined and the economy was reduced.
Since 2011, Sinaloa has a year that will be remembered for its economic history, being related to the first year of Mario Lopez Valdez government, which generated great expectations for the economic development of the region, but due to the climate adversity of the first year of Mario Lopez Valdez government, there was no growth, but the main economic indicators declined.
The low February temperatures not only caused losses for the agriculture sector, but also limited the potential of the state economy to grow, causing a general contraction of the economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly supported by the historic fall of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which affected other economic sectors.
The report on the damaged areas caused by the frost, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, reported that 78.03 percent of the affected areas suffered total damage and the rest of 21.07 percent suffered partial damage.
The fall in economic activity has resulted in a constant increase in unemployment in the state, from January to March 55,053 Sinaloa citizens were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the economically active population for the second quarter the rate changed to 5.28 percent, and between July and September the rate continued to increase to 6.19 percent, a rate that in terms of number of people represents more than 74.000 unemployed Sinaloa citizens.
Lower liquidity
While unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multi-factorial, for economist Gerardo Lopez Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the public policy action.
These are increasing unemployment which is caused by several factors, including loss of liquidity in the market for the purpose of a resource constraint in the Congress to combat money laundering.
Stopped Immigration
Lopez Cervantes added that in the increase of unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
The number of people who leave the state in search of a job abroad has been restricted, first of all due to the difficulty to enter and secondly because they have too many difficulties in finding a job, that group of people is staying and demanding jobs in the state, causing unemployment to rise.
Informality
The labor market analysis of Sinaloa gets worse when considering the high level of informality in working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the active population in the state works without being listed as workers to any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another state labor reminder is low wages; the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labor and Social Welfare.
The monthly average income of Sinaloa workers was, until September, 5.352 pesos, well below the national average of 7.375 pesos.
Contracts for FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and high unemployment rate, in 2011 the state foreign direct investment totaled 630.697 dollars, which represents a 87.74 percent decline compared to the same period last year.
The State Government’s Economic Development Ministry accounted for a total investment of 17.280.000 pesos in the year, mainly occurring in tertiary sector companies.
Debt
Following the economic downturn, the state government asked for a credit of 3 billion pesos, which would be for the investment in 18 municipalities, in order to reactivate the state economy.
Reactions
For business representatives, the first year of Mario Lopez Valdes government shows a lack of capacity of the government.
Miguel Loredo Lopez, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of various sectors, including the state government itself.
The performance of the economy in Sinaloa this year has been very poor, we have to work hard to regain the ground lost this year, in 2012 we must redouble our efforts, we failed to align the efforts of all and above all the good and coordinated effort of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better.
Economic slowing
Lopez Loredo said that the events such as early frost this year restricted the state economy and its performance and growth was restricted.
The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost, which does not turn fast enough to produce an acceptable flow of the processes, products and services and thus, at the end of the year we are closing it below our expectations.
Redefining the vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers' Association of the Republic of Sinaloa, said that the state must prosecute the most dynamic productive activities.
Overall, we found that there has been work on, we believe it is necessary to develop a long term program that defines the vocation and economic course of the state, it is important to detonate all the material and human potential resources that Sinaloa has.
Work to Do
