The Quintet took the country on tour to celebrate two decades of experience.
'Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true'
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam says the band is ready to offer one of its best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
The band says that for the member it was a dream turned into reality playing in the country.
This was stated by the bassist and founding member, Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva from Brazil last week.
The group is on South American zone within the tour celebrating two decades of work and Sunday 20th will make its only stop in Central America.
The day will be held at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 pm, together with the band of Los Angeles The X and the nationals Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt of the conversation, which is available in The Nation.
For your Costa Rican fans, is it a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica?
Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far has been great.
Although I have only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation, it is a beautiful country and I think we can stay for a few days there.
Then we are excited to bring our music to the city.
I ask this because there is a kind of devotion to the band; the fans live with intense intensity the days before the concert.
What do you say to your most loyal followers?
Thank you for staying with us through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thanks for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get here.
Some people when they hear your concert describe it as the most important show of the year.
What is this?
Some of the most important shows we have played over the past 21 years occurred in the last couple of weeks.
We had a few wonderful shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that this has prepared us for the Costa Rica concert.
Really, we are very eager to play there.
We love this country, we love surf and the jungle, for both things Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have many friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are incredible.
My friends always go to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, and that's how we learned about surfing through people who love surfing.
Viewing the tour, one can say that you have been making great shows with lots of songs.
What are you preparing for the presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never played there before, there are no restrictions on what we can do.
The best show possible will be with a good variety of songs, we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How do you get involved?
It is partly because we have nine discs and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's difficult to pick which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that have not been played for a while, it keeps us focused and surprises because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked them and that we may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also makes it more interesting for the people.
With this tour you are celebrating 20 years of experience.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all you have made?
Yes, absolutely.
First, I think no one of us could ever imagine we would be in a rock band and doing this for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We count on Blessings and we are very excited to continue making music together.
We all love each other and love making music.
We are fortunate to travel to places in the world where we always wanted to go.
The things cannot be better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental part of the rise of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of that group of great bands.
We are good friends of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is amazing when a movement arises from a group of friends and it is unusual.
The usual sight of a city is a band of a city, but it is much more strange when five or ten bands emerge from the same city.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
I still play with some of them sometimes.
The last year we were in Canada with Alice in Chains and we saw Soundgarden in its tour, so we are fortunate to be friends with all of them and we are honored to be part of the Seattle sound that aroused.
It is also strange that a band like yours remains united with same members for so long.
Together we have been for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which is a long time than many bands lasted.
First, I think we are all lucky to be still alive and secondly, we all care about others.
We are close friends and, thanks to this, there have also been open musical avenues that allow each to experiment.
We trust each other with our music and this cannot be better.
Your relationship to fame has not been easy, but thanks to your success you have been able to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find balance.
We take care not to be too much on tour because it is easy to fall into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
While people are there for the music, that reminds you to respect the music and what it brings, without thinking about being famous and being a rock star, something that no one really cares about.
How do you remember your other project Manother Love Bone?
I think we write good songs and at the beginning was a great thing.
We were almost three years in a band and never released a single album until after the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
The most important thing is that we are still close friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and always laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
It was a remarkable man and we miss him.
The national band Las Robertas will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
What do you know about the work of Eddie Vedder?
The production sent us several videos proposals and that was the band we liked most.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
It is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I do not know.
The song is very catchy and I think he does this with the first thing that comes to his mind.
As a bassist, what influences influence you?
There are so many.
Within the first that come to my mind are Jerry Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski ...
There are so many I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam maintain grunge relevant despite being no longer a fad?
I think all of us feel disconnected from the word grunge.
If I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all that came at the same time.
The first recording had darker content, and now has become more positive.
How do you explain this change?
The album is interesting because there are a couple of songs on the album that may sound lighter but they can sound positive.
With both, when Ed played them, I cried when I heard them.
The two songs represent that for me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still make music that is dark.
