MSS announces a protocol for obesity gene identification
Social Security directs a research to find the gene for obesity in children and young people; it is supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Mexican Social Security Institute (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting research to discover the gene for obesity in children and young people, called the protocol of 'Genetics of obesity in children and young people', which will provide counting on markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the Head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of Specialty Hospital, XXI Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz Lopez, explained that the research unit was integrated with a multi-disciplinary team of doctors, nurses and social workers.
The team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (NIPH) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
The research invites the population entitled or not to participate by going to the participant sport units of the MSSI in the Valley of Mexico, where children will be tested every Saturday from 8:00 o'clock.
The protocol started in Cuauhtémoc sports unit (West Mexico State) and since October 8th the activity is held in the Netzahualcoyotl Sport Unit (East Mexico State).
Once the goal of bringing 500 to 600 children, the study will continue in the Independence Sport Unit (South the Mexico City) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (North the Mexico City).
The purpose of this research is to understand the components and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and identify in children and young Mexicans the risk factors for the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
The World Diabetes Day is celebrated on November 14 and the goal is to collect three thousand children and young people between 6 and 14 years with consent and parental supervision for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family hereditary disease, in order to prevent risk factors that may cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
The anthropometric measures (weight, height, and waist circumference), blood pressure measurements, and determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetic (seeking to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz Lopez said that this research reflects the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in children.
