UNAM asphalt would prevent potholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture with the best performance, regardless of the environment and temperature.
If the signal is followed, it would require about 200 thousand potholes every rain season in the Metropolitan Area of Mexico, according to Rafael Herrera Najera, a research fellow at the Chemistry Faculty (CF) of the UNAM, who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavement is adequate, potholes could be reduced or even eliminated.
In his lecture A technological view of pothole, issued under the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing a polymer modified asphalt to produce a mixture with similar characteristics to asphalt but with better mechanical strength both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north, to improve its performance and thus reduce the formation of potholes.
The asphalt, the heavier oil part is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and other of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the road surface its viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt is based on the fact that at high temperatures near 180 degrees it acts like a liquid at 120° C, its viscosity is high and at 50 degrees Celsius is nearly solid, while at low temperatures it becomes fragile.
This means that the street asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to the environmental conditions and temperature, said the chemical engineer.
CF researcher observed that the city streets are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of material, of which the last three are asphalt.
The most superficial layer is the asphalt, composed of small stones dipped into the asphalt and then compacted.
The stones that form this cover, he added, are dipped with asphalt.
When driving vehicles and generating effort, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt it would spread even better, said the chemical engineer.
Then, he added, is placed a final layer called rolling covering, which is made of fine stone material, meaning sand is also dipped into the asphalt.
This is the layer that will be in contact with the wheel of the vehicle, and it must have better mechanical strength than the asphalt covering and provide road friction.
As the part of the pavement that will receive and diffuse the effort, the rolling cover also requires proper thickness and material to be considered.
The weather, especially humidity and temperature variations are also important factors to consider, especially water, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt.
When the ground is wet, water diffuses inside the cover and is hard to get out, causing softening of all layers of the pavement and thus causing potholes.
In the formation of a pothole, he says, the first to wear is the rolling cover and only after that affects the asphalt.
Also a member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each layer of the pavement should be always adjusted to the vehicle load and ensure this fulfillment.
Rafael Herrera said that there is still much to investigate and work on the asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already available and even help repair potholes with ease and without high temperatures.
