North Stream, a new portal for the entry of Russian gas into Europe
North Stream gasduct connecting Western Europe and Russia directly along the Baltic Sea has been commissioned.
It is expected to supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the giant Russian gas producer, wanted to celebrate the event with a "bang."
The Baltic Sea was a scenic spot for 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, to inaugurate North Stream, the new gasduct that directly links Russia and Germany under the sea.
Together, the German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russia president Dmitry Medvedev, and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new gasduct, 27,5 million million cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe via a first pipeline of 1 224 km linking Saint Petersburg to the Mecklenburg-Pomerania region.
The second pipeline is due to be ready by the end of 2012, allowing the delivery of total 55 million cubic metres of gas, equivalent to the total French consumption.
The possibility of constructing a second pipeline of the same course is already under discussion.
Gazprom is proud to ensure the timely completion of this huge project.
The project was fiercely contested by Poland and the Baltic States.
North Stream will in fact allow direct gas delivery to Germany, avoiding any third country (Poland or Ukraine).
This two countries will lose some of their power: they will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close access to West European markets.
The most critical point of the debate was when Warsaw took North Stream new "German-Soviet pact," referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
It is apolitically sensitive topic.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is gaining more security for its supplies.
The cost of depriving Europe of energy is at the price of depriving Europe of energy, since the project has created a breach between eastern and western Europe.
Russia has successfully achieved in less than five years, in achieving its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume large quantities of gas and whose deposits are declining.
The gasduct is a new artery that links us organically, which is a new artery that links us organically.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of Gazprom headquarters, present largely at Lubmin, the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gasduct is also technical.
The undersea pipeline is made of steel embedded in concrete, to protect it from ships' anchors.
Ir remains on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 metres.
To construct it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to the second World War.
The hundred were removed or destroyed as a precaution, says Jens Müller, spokesman of North Stream company.
It was also necessary to multiply the steps of protecting the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal serpent, weight equivalent to 242 Eiffel towers, with no breaks throughout its length, no valves and no maintenance stations.
The control platform was provided on the level of Sweden, but the project manager abandoned it because Sweden was not keen to see a Russian State company become permanently on its shores.
In case of accident we stop the passage of gas for at least one minute.
In case of leak, the gas contained in the gasduct therefore escapes into the air.
The constructors believe that the welds will only leak every 100 000 years.
The surveillance of the gasduct is provided by an undersea robot, pulled by a ship for outside observation, and by an apparatus circulating within the gasduct.
The cigar shape is introduced into the 1-metre wide pipeline, and it is pushed along by the gas.
After 3 complete days of travel at a speed of 3 metres per second, it provides precise information about any metal deformation.
The gasduct was designed to work for 50 years without even the smallest repair.
The gas circulation is implemented by its pressure.
This is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies combined their forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shareholding.
Others are the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Netherlands Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
This five companies have created a joint enterprise called North Stream, which is responsible for constructing and running the gasduct.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Gazprom next leased to this company for 20renewable years, the entire capacity of gas transport.
Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, whatever may be the quantity of gas transported.
The financing of the gasduct was provided to the extent of 30% by the shareholders and of 70% by Bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 million Euros for the two pipelines.
The GDF Suez investment will be about 240 million.
The minority shareholders are certain to recover their costs, since Gazprom assumes the entire risk.
The gasduct emerges from the Baltic Sea at Lubmin on a sandy littoral with conifers.
4.5 metre high valves form the gas exit.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and specific gravity of arriving gas before being transported into German gasducts.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic cubic cubic cubic of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity this will be 3 million an hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand card.
Created fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine will restore the taste of writing.
It is a scent of adventure, of hours sent in writing by the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easy to recognise, by its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its broken white pages, as if aged over time.
The Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a designer notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant of the company, has assumed the responsibility for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, mole skin, which is varnished cotton used for covering benches, for example.
This type of notebook is said to be highly prized by writers and travellers.
'Moleskine has been updated to meet current taste for an old and forgotten object, which was an avant-garde artist's icon up to the XXth century', added Maria Sebregondi.
Success is a combination of success.
Within 2006 and 2010, sales rose by 25% to reach 12.7 million units.
One has travelled far from the first years of production, when only 3000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine is crossing the Italian frontier and is exporting to 70 countries, from France to USA.
The typical buyer is difficult to identify, since the notebook attracts equally a businessman, a student and a professional.
Moleskin consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had only 12 employees at the start, now has almost 100 and two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks to Fnac libraries, small shops in town centres and has become well known.
”We follow the spirit of the times and this need for new ways of writing, despite the rise of e-mail,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature is a signature of Moleskine, recently launching an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, it also launched a leopardskin pattern cover on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Through the success and cultural aura, Moleskine diversified its products into handbags, pens, computer bags.
The success of the collaboration which aroused envy; in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, to write a new page in the history of Moleskine.
How is the unemployment rate of handicapped workers so high?
Some 19% of handicapped persons are looking for work.
The 15th week for the handicapped work starts today.
The rate of unemployment of the handicapped is still twice as high as the average, namely 19%, versus 9% for the general population.
Discoding?
No, says Eric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association which organises the week for the employment of the handicapped.
The progress achieved since 15 years ago is considerable.
"At that time the unemployment rate was not 2x but 3x as high."
There is still a huge amount to do.
It must be added that for the handicapped, the obstacles to obtaining work still exist.
Their age is quite young: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
Their qualifications are very low, 80% do not have the "bac" and out of the 2.3 million students in high education only 10 000 are handicapped.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is widespread, with 85% for the handicapped versus 38% on average.
Overall, all these are criteria that significantly complicate employment and which constitute the nub of the problem, according to Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit handicapped workers.
Here are some brakes.
It is hard to speak about mentalities, which change but too slowly.
The study conducted in April by the association IMS-Cité Corporate Partnership showed that the managers questioned had low level of knowledge of handicap, with an overrepresentation of persons in wheelchairs, mental or intellectually deficient persons.
Results - private companies employing over 20 persons are still far from meeting the objective of employing the 6% of handicapped workers, fixed by a law from 1987.
The last known figures from 2008 have a ratio of 2.6%.
Currently we are around 3% of businesses who do not observe this law.
Proof: The number of "taxed" establishments, as well the paid amounts, have declined between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million Euros).
The law of 2005, which raised the contributions, has caused strong pressure on companies, explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a rise of consciousness, particularly in large groups."
According to the ministry of employment, only 59% of establishments employing between 20 and 49 persons are employed, compared to 82% of establishments employing between 100 and 199 persons.
